# Post-Skill-Creation Pipeline

When a new skill is created or an existing SKILL.md is significantly modified (not a trivial typo fix), run the following 3-step pipeline **after** the skill creation/modification is complete and verified.

## Trigger Conditions

This rule applies when:
- A new `.cursor/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` file is created
- An existing SKILL.md is substantially rewritten (new sections, new references, changed workflow)

This rule does NOT apply when:
- Only fixing a typo or formatting in an existing SKILL.md
- Modifying reference files without changing SKILL.md
- Running bulk operations (cursor-sync, skill-optimizer audit across all skills)

## Pipeline

Run these 3 steps sequentially after the skill is created/modified:

### Step 1: Setup Doctor (prerequisites check)

Check if the new/modified skill introduces any new prerequisites (CLI tools, env vars, packages, MCP servers) that are not yet installed.

```
/setup-doctor --group <relevant-group>
```

If the skill doesn't map to a specific group, run `--env` to check for any new env var requirements. Report any missing prerequisites to the user.

### Step 2: Skill Guide Sync (documentation update)

Ensure the new/modified skill has a corresponding entry in the skill guides documentation.

```
/skill-guide-sync --scope <skill-name>
```

This updates the skill guide index and generates any missing documentation entries.

### Step 3: AutoSkill Evolve (evolution tracking)

Run a dry-run evolution check to see if the new skill overlaps with or should be merged with existing skills.

```
/autoskill-evolve --dry-run --scope recent
```

If overlaps are detected, report them to the user for review before proceeding.

## Execution Notes

- Steps 1-3 are advisory — they report findings but do not block the skill creation
- If the user explicitly says they will handle these later, skip the pipeline
- For bulk skill operations (e.g., cursor-sync importing 10+ skills), run the pipeline once at the end, not per-skill
- Keep the pipeline lightweight — use `--dry-run` and scoped modes to minimize overhead
